<section class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">Understanding the Real Math Behind Gambling</h2>
  
  <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
      Casinos use something called <strong>Return to Player (RTP)</strong> percentages to make you think you have a decent chance of winning. But here's what they don't want you to understand:
    </p>

    <div class="bg-warning-50 border-l-4 border-warning-500 p-4 mb-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-warning-800 mb-2">The House Always Wins</h3>
      <p class="text-warning-700 mb-0">
        Even with a "high" RTP of 96%, the casino keeps 4% of every dollar played. Over time, you <em>will</em> lose money.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-900">Real RTP Examples from Popular Providers:</h3>
    
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-800 mb-2">"Better" RTPs (Still Bad for You)</h4>
        <ul class="text-green-700 space-y-1">
          <li>• NetEnt slots: ~96% RTP</li>
          <li>• Microgaming: ~95-96% RTP</li>
          <li>• Play'n GO: ~94-96% RTP</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-green-600 mt-2"><strong>Reality:</strong> You lose $4-6 for every $100 played</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800 mb-2">Worse RTPs (Terrible for You)</h4>
        <ul class="text-red-700 space-y-1">
          <li>• Some Pragmatic Play: ~88-92% RTP</li>
          <li>• Many mobile games: ~80-85% RTP</li>
          <li>• Shady operators: As low as 70% RTP</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-red-600 mt-2"><strong>Reality:</strong> You lose $15-30 for every $100 played</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-800 mb-3">What RTP Really Means</h3>
      <p class="text-blue-700 mb-3">
        RTP is calculated over <strong>millions</strong> of spins. It doesn't mean you'll get 96% back in your session. You might lose everything in minutes, or rarely win big and think you're ahead - but the math ensures the casino profits.
      </p>
      <p class="text-blue-700 font-medium">
        The more you play, the closer your results get to the RTP - and the RTP always favors the house.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-900">Other Hidden Tricks:</h3>
    
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-800">Variable RTPs</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-700">Many games let casinos choose the RTP - the same slot might be 96% at one casino and 88% at another.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-800">Volatility Confusion</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-700">High volatility games pay out less frequently but with bigger wins, making you think you're "due" for a big win.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-800">Near-Miss Programming</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-700">Slots are programmed to show "almost wins" more often than random chance would suggest, keeping you playing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>